01:13:41.180 --> 01:13:44.380
You call that--you can view
that death as the fear of

01:13:44.380 --> 01:13:45.180
castration.
 

01:13:45.180 --> 01:13:49.726
I think it's an extreme version
of that, so I would agree with

01:13:49.726 --> 01:13:52.560
what I hear is behind your
question.

01:13:55.989 --> 01:13:56.439
Yes?
 

01:13:56.439 --> 01:14:00.599
Student:  So why does he
draw us into that allegory of

01:14:00.599 --> 01:14:02.538
Medusa and petrified love?
 

01:14:02.538 --> 01:14:05.594
Prof: Well he-- I--you
mean if it's--the question is

01:14:05.594 --> 01:14:08.805
why does he draw us into that
allegory if it's about petrified

01:14:08.805 --> 01:14:09.279
love?
 

01:14:09.279 --> 01:14:12.680
Right, this is the question and
I presume--

01:14:12.680 --> 01:14:14.130
I don't want to explain your
question,

01:14:14.130 --> 01:14:17.619
I have to answer your question,
but I presume that your

01:14:17.619 --> 01:14:22.760
question stems from your--
this kind of concern you have.

01:14:22.760 --> 01:14:25.578
If it's such a private story,
why us?

01:14:25.578 --> 01:14:27.880
In what way are we involved in
that?

01:14:27.880 --> 01:14:29.470
This is his story, right?
 

01:14:29.470 --> 01:14:32.569
The answer that I could give is
yes,

01:14:32.569 --> 01:14:36.353
this is--can be seen as Dante's
own confession and the

01:14:36.353 --> 01:14:40.850
confession and that's why I read
the passage from Augustine,

01:14:40.850 --> 01:14:43.006
from Augustine's own
Confessions:

01:14:43.006 --> 01:14:45.658
a confession that can also be
exemplary to us.

01:14:45.658 --> 01:14:49.639
And because he thinks,
I think, that there are no

01:14:49.639 --> 01:14:54.033
experiences that are irreducibly
private and therefore

01:14:54.033 --> 01:14:55.359
unshareable.
 

01:14:55.359 --> 01:14:59.421
It's part of the concern of
this writing--of this writer,

01:14:59.421 --> 01:15:03.627
that anything that will happen
to him we are--I have to say

01:15:03.627 --> 01:15:04.279
this.
 

01:15:04.279 --> 01:15:08.872
We are going to find moments
when he tells us its night

01:15:08.872 --> 01:15:13.381
dreams, pretty heavy night
dreams, but treated with an

01:15:13.381 --> 01:15:16.189
extraordinary,
I think, care.

01:15:16.189 --> 01:15:19.680
We are going to have his--we
are going to enter into his

01:15:19.680 --> 01:15:23.170
psyche, why part of--way of
entering into his psyche?

01:15:23.170 --> 01:15:28.578
Because he has to understand
not only how shareable his

01:15:28.578 --> 01:15:32.885
experience is,
but also, what is the root of

01:15:32.885 --> 01:15:35.890
the way we make decisions?
 

01:15:35.890 --> 01:15:40.899
Do--can we really be ever all
the time vigilant?

01:15:40.899 --> 01:15:42.060
This is in the case of the
dream.

01:15:42.060 --> 01:15:46.439
Am I responsible if I perceive
the world in a certain way?

01:15:46.439 --> 01:15:49.930
Am I responsible if dreams come
to me in a certain way?

01:15:49.930 --> 01:15:52.368
Then, am I accountable for this
kind of dreams?

01:15:52.368 --> 01:15:57.159
The concern is always that of
trying to delimit an area where

01:15:57.159 --> 01:16:01.470
there is some common ground
between his experiences and

01:16:01.470 --> 01:16:05.274
ours,
and that's the transaction of

01:16:05.274 --> 01:16:06.310
allegory.
 

01:16:11.100 --> 01:16:12.529
Yes?
 

01:16:12.529 --> 01:16:14.038
Student:  At the end of
